# 1. Logical Structure of Mathematical Claims

## Quantifier Forms (Critical)

| Form | Meaning | Common Pitfall |
|---|---|---|
| \( \forall x\,P(x) \) | Holds for all inputs | Forgetting arbitrariness |
| \( \exists x\,P(x) \) | At least one witness | Not constructing witness |
| \( \forall x\exists y \) | Choice depends on \(x\) | Treating as uniform |
| \( \exists y\forall x \) | Single global choice | Illegally letting \(y\) vary |

---

## Negation Rules

| Statement | Correct Negation |
|---|---|
| \( \forall x\,P(x) \) | \( \exists x:\neg P(x) \) |
| \( \exists x\,P(x) \) | \( \forall x:\neg P(x) \) |
| \( P\Rightarrow Q \) | \( P\land\neg Q \) |

**ML relevance:** bounds, guarantees, and convergence statements often fail due to incorrect negation.

